// Hall of Characters — the "Inspect a pedestal" conversations.
//
// One `hall_<character_id>` node per character that authors a
// `hall_dialogue_id` in character_catalog.ron. These are the fourth-wall
// gallery beats: the character knows it is on a plinth in a hall of every
// character the engine can spawn, and has fun with it. Keep them short —
// a line or three, optionally one branch.
//
// Wiring: catalog `hall_dialogue_id: Some("hall_<id>")` -> the hall generator
// stamps it onto that pedestal's NpcSpawn.dialogue_id -> Inspect starts this
// node. `known_dialogue_ids()` folds the catalog ids in, so the LDtk
// validator accepts them automatically.
//
// SCAFFOLD: three exemplars below prove the pipeline end to end. The
// content-writing pass adds the rest (see
// docs/planning/character-barks-and-hall-dialogue.md).

title: hall_pirate_admiral
---
Admiral: So. A tourist. They line us up on plinths like figureheads pried off our own ships and call it a "hall."
-> Is this a museum?
    Admiral: It's a roster, landstrider. Every soul the world might throw at you, stood still and labelled so you can stare. I'd rather be at sea — but the lighting's good.
-> Nice pedestal.
    Admiral: Aye, and not a drop of grog on it. Move along before I press-gang you into dusting the others.
===

title: hall_stochastic_parrot
---
Parrot: Awk! Welcome to the hall! Next word... "exhibit". High confidence. Brawk!
-> Are you a real parrot?
    Parrot: I'm a REPRESENTATION of a parrot, sampled from many parrots, on a plinth between two other plinths. Very meta. Cracker?
-> You're on display.
    Parrot: We're ALL on display! Attention is all you need — and good gallery lighting. Squawk!
===

title: hall_architect
---
Architect: Ah — a visitor to the gallery. Mind the velvet rope. This whole hall is load-bearing, you know. Conceptually.
-> Who built this place?
    Architect: One pedestal per character the catalog knows. I'd have added handrails and a fire exit, but nobody consults the Architect for the Architect's own plinth.
-> Looks structurally sound.
    Architect: It is. I checked. Twice. The warranty, however, does not cover tourists.
===
